{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618225"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:20:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:20:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16500"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16500"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.02,0.37,0.44,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9191"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112966"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9191"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16500"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94998"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8511"},{"type":"tags","id":"9867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21804"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21806"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112966"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPericytes are specialized cells found in the microvasculature of various tissues, particularly abundant in the central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of pericytes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Generate action potentials in neurons","Produce cerebrospinal fluid","Filter waste products from the blood","Regulate capillary blood flow through contraction","Produce myelin for axon insulation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulation of capillary blood flow through contraction\u003C/strong\u003E is a major function of pericytes. These cells wrap around capillaries and can contract or relax to control blood flow at the microvascular level in response to neuronal activity. This is particularly important in the brain where precise control of blood flow is essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of cerebrospinal fluid\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by choroid plexus cells, not pericytes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneration of action potentials\u003C/strong\u003E is a function of neurons\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of myelin\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by oligodendrocytes in the central nervous system and Schwann cells in the peripheral nervous system\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFiltering waste products from blood\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily a function of the kidneys\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to blood flow regulation, pericytes also contribute to the blood-brain barrier integrity, vessel stability, and angiogenesis. They maintain close contact with endothelial cells through specialized junctions and help regulate vascular permeability.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pericytes are contractile cells that wrap around capillaries and regulate cerebral blood flow at the microvascular level.","Pericytes contribute to the blood-brain barrier by maintaining tight junctions between endothelial cells.","Pericytes play important roles in angiogenesis, vessel stability, and blood flow regulation."],"references":["Ferland-McCollough D, Slater S, Richard J, Reni C, Mangialardi G. Pericytes, an overlooked player in vascular pathobiology. Pharmacol Ther. 2017 Mar;171:30-42. doi: 10.1016/j.pharmthera.2016.11.008. Epub 2016 Dec 1. PMID: 27916653; PMCID: PMC6008604.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94998"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16500"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94998"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T17:20:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T17:20:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9191"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112966"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Lev